        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                <date>Nov. 24. 1854</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I am much obliged<lb/> to you for the flattering notice, with which
                you have<lb/> returned your thanks to me in your last Number of the<lb/> Occident,
                and also the attention you have paid to<lb/> my report of Laying the Corner Stone of
                the Con-<lb/>-gregation. I have heard many expressions of<lb/> admiration for your
                own notice or <del>preparatory</del> introductory<lb/> remarks of the Laying the
                Corner Stone, but also regret<lb/> that many did not get their Occidents.</p>
            <p>Your <placeName>Marysville</placeName> subscribers tell me, that they have<lb/> paid
                    <persName>Mayer</persName> their dues; <persName>Mr. F. M. Reinhart</persName> of<lb/>
                <placeName>Marysville</placeName> has paid me $3â€” though he had<lb/> paid it to
                    <persName>Mayer</persName>; he requests me to inform you<lb/> that he desires to
                discontinue his subscription.<lb/>
                <persName>Messrs. B. Kohn</persName>, <persName>Stein Eisner &amp; Co</persName>,
                    <persName>Lehman &amp; Co</persName> &amp;<lb/>
                <persName>Genson</persName>, have left their places of Residence, and<lb/> if you do
                continue to send them the Occident, you<lb/> will never, I do not believe receive
                any dues form them.<lb/>
                <persName>Mr I &amp; J Labbat</persName> has told me, that he has sent<lb/> you the
                money for the Bible, which he has received<lb/> from you. I have delivered the
                sunday school<lb/> Books, but was unable as yet to get the money,<lb/> but I have
                the promise of <persName>H. Seligman</persName> soon to re-</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>ceive it. On the <date>22d</date> inst. the Eureka Benevolent<lb/> Society gave a
                Ball, which was well conducted; the so-<lb/>-ciety have cleared by it about $1000;
                they are in<lb/> a very prosperous condition and have 120 members.<lb/> Send an
                Occident and some Back Numbers to<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Cohn</persName> care of <persName>Barnett Keesing</persName>
                <placeName>Box 488 San Francisco</placeName><lb/> whose subscription I got.</p>
            <p>In about 3 months I shall, please God, be in<lb/>
                <placeName>Phila.</placeName>, before my Departure I hope to be able<lb/> to send
                you some money; it is harder to<lb/> get trifling amounts generally speaking, due
                you<lb/> than it is in the states. <persName>Mr. Steppacher</persName> might<lb/>
                perhaps suit you the best as the man you have re<lb/>-marked in your last Letter you
                would desire for<lb/> selling your works, as he is shamos for the<lb/> Congregation
                Emanu-El; I have spoken upon that<lb/> subject to him, and he tells me, he would
                be<lb/> willing to make some arrangements with you.</p>
            <p><persName>Mr. &amp; J. Labbat</persName> has informed me that he has<lb/> transmitted
                to you the Result of the<lb/> Election, which has taken place some 6 weeks ago,<lb/>
                in which you have perceived that <persName>Dr. Eckman</persName> was<lb/> taken up
                by the Congregation at $2000 salary for<lb/> one year; he has now his school
                regularly<lb/> established for the Instruction of the children<lb/> in Hebrew, who
                make admirable progress<lb/> in their studies; he gives 3 times in the week<lb/>
                Lessons, besides the sunday school, which is<lb/> under his superintendence; 40
                children attend now</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>In conclusion let me extend you my best<lb/> wishes for your Prosperity</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Whilst I remain In Haste</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Cauffman &amp; Meyers</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <persName>Mr &amp; Mrs Roggenburger</persName>
            </p>
            <p>desire their kind Regards</p>
            <p>to you</p>
